Nicely done, there is hope for you yet!
Now let’s see, what do we have here? Looks like you are going to have to do more than just drive in a straight line for this one!
Not to worry, as the Bot class contains another method. This method is called ‘Turn’ and is used to get round corners. It also uses a string parameter.
A string parameter what is that?! For the ‘Move’ method the parameter is an integer; a whole number and by parameter I mean the number which goes between the brackets. So for the ‘Move’ method the parameter is an integer value which determines how many spaces you want the bot to move.
So what about the ‘Turn’ method? What do you mean by ‘string’?

data.name: richTextBox2.Text
data.value:
The parameter for the ‘Turn’ method is a string. You can think of a string as being a word with upper and lower case letters but it can also contain numbers, symbols and spaces.
Here are some examples: “Foo”, “bar”, “£3.50”, “42”, “joeblogs@code_bot.com”, “the number 8”
So they can pretty much be anything? Listen up because this bit is important: STRINGS ARE ALWAYS TYPED BETWEEN DOUBLE QUOTATION MARKS!! Sorry for yelling but I cannot stress to you how important that is! In programming “42” is different to 42. 42 is an integer, “42” is a string, understand?
The bot can turn “left” or “right” so put that in the parameter for the ‘Turn’ method, keep in mind that they are case sensitive.
I have jabbered on enough. Let’s Go!
